<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-05T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-05T02:00:00-05:00" n="22" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.0012/575</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GGW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Guthrie</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-05T16:00:00+09:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">November 5, 1914, 4 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8 a.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Your telegram of October 16, 6 p.m. I have again spoken to the Minister
                            for Foreign Affairs about peace treaty but have failed to secure any
                            expression from him. From the trend of his remarks I infer that he is
                            not ready to adopt the policy of such treaties. He is also inclined to
                            the belief that the United States and Japan have conflicting views in
                            regard to China. There is also always present strong dissatisfaction
                            about California legislation intensified by fear that hostile
                            legislation will be passed. We can hardly hope for a favorable response
                            at least until that fear is removed.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GGW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Guthrie</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>